qas.question: What defeat led to Prussia having to swear its allegiance to Napoleon?
What city did King Frederick William use to flee Prussia?
What year did Napoleon end of the War of the Fourth Coalition?

plausible_answers.text: General Count Friedrich Adolf von Kalkreuth

qas.question: Who was the leader of the army Napoleon beat at the Battle of Friedland?
What military leader did Napoleon beat at the Battle of Jena-Auerstedt?

context: After the disastrous defeat of the <b3_0><b6_0>Prussian<b6_0/><b3_0/> Army at the <a0_0>Battle of Jena-Auerstedt<a0_0/> in 1806, Napoleon occupied Berlin and had the officials of the Prussian General Directory swear an oath of allegiance to him, while King Frederick William III and his consort Louise fled via <a1_0>Königsberg<a1_0/> and the Curonian Spit to Memel. The French troops immediately took up pursuit but were delayed in the Battle of Eylau on 9 February <a2_0>1807<a2_0/> by an East Prussian contingent under <b5_0>General Anton Wilhelm von L'Estocq<b5_0/>. Napoleon had to stay at the Finckenstein Palace, but in May, after a siege of 75 days, his troops led by Marshal François Joseph Lefebvre were able to capture the city Danzig, which had been tenaciously defended by <b4_0>General Count Friedrich Adolf von Kalkreuth<b4_0/>. On 14 June, Napoleon ended the War of the Fourth Coalition with his victory at the Battle of Friedland. Frederick William and Queen Louise met with Napoleon for peace negotiations, and on 9 July the Prussian king signed the Treaty of Tilsit.
